@Remark ============================================================================

@Node "Introduction" "Why another startup controller ?"

@{u}Overview@{uu}

 RawStartup is a Startup-Sequence selector. You can define an
 individual startup-sequence and assign it to any key of your
 keyboard. This means you can have as many startup-sequences
 as you have keys :)
 During the boot sequence you can press a key to select which
 configuration should be used. The main advantage of raw startup
 is that it produces absolutely @{b}no output@{ub} - no text and no
 graphics. So it's ideal for those with monitors that can't
 display 15kHz modes.
 Please refer to @{"operation" link "Operation"} for further details.


@{u}Why another startup controller ?@{uu}


 Well, I've tried out almost all startup controllers
 available on the AmiNET but none of them satisfied
 my needs so I decided to write my own.

 @{b}Two good reasons:@{ub}

 The problem with most of the other controllers is that they
 insist on some kind of output which might be neat but if
 you run your Amiga with a @{b}graphics card@{ub} and a multisync
 monitor which isn't capable of displaying the @{b}15kHz mode@{ub}
 the best you will see is a distorted screen. To  avoid
 this problem you always had to copy the EnvARC: files to
 the ram and run IPrefs before you could choose. But for
 some programs (like Shapeshifter) I want all the memory
 available and not fill the ram with some variables I don't
 need at the moment.

 Even if they don't open a special gui they will open a
 CLI window and if you haven't run IPrefs before either
 you'll get bothered with a requester that says "Intuition
 would like to reset the workbench screen" (or something
 simmilar) as long as the window is open => no bootpicture
 can be showed or the monitor has to switch often between
 different frequencies which might shorten its lifespan.


 @{b}Result:@{ub}

 So the result is a very "raw" program called RawStartup.
 All it will do while your amiga boots is to check if a
 key is pressed and if so it will try to use the according
 startup script as a default startup script.
 So if you don't press any key the last startup script you
 selected will be executed. That's it.


 @{b}Future:@{ub}

 I don't know what else RawStartup should be able to do but
 one thing I will never do is including something that leads
 to graphical output (like password protection or whatsoever).
 RawStartup's main purpose is to serve users with graphics
 cards as a cheap but effectife boot selector.

@EndNode

